If you believe that people can heal, change, or learn from their mistakes, it’s important to discourage the idea that people are disposable or defined by their worst moments. Empathy is required. Unfortunately not everyone practices it.

The goal is for the person who offended them to lose friendships, lose community, lose financial stability, lose personal safety, inflict mental abuse, and remove any accountability from the person leading the campaign.

It never solves anything, but in practicing cancellation the person finds support from other people. 

This can be weaponized to cause further harm.

Cancel campaigns can happen when a lie is exposed. It may be because someone is vindictive or can’t let go after a break-up. Those who instigate them are seeking validation of their feelings. They want their anger to transfer. They want to abuse and inflict pain.

What I’ve learned is that not everyone believes in restorative justice. Some believe that a person is only their worst action. Some believe that no apology or punishment is enough for even minor violations. Some people exaggerate and lie.

The level of harm caused is reduced when mediation is available and communication is open. The community can be involved to listen or lend support to either party. We share the impacts of the incident and agree to an appropriate response.
Restorative Justice is focused on healing. Cancel Culture is focused on harm.
Our responses to those mistakes should be at a level relative to the action, the harm caused, as well as remorsefulness of the accused.
People make mistakes.
Attempts to cancel people goes against the aim of restorative justice.

Anyway, today I thought of the last time I cried. Like a real one. It's been a while. Maybe cause I'm no longer giving tears to those who don't deserve them. Maybe cause I'm happy again.
But onward and elsewhere. Like physical wounds, emotional ones heal. I know I'm happier now than when I started this whole thing and that's the only metric of success I'm basing my life on.

I'm still impacted by 12/20/20. I couldn't cry at my abuela's funeral. I feel emotionally distant when I don't want to be. My social anxiety now makes going to public spaces feel like torture rather than a joy.

With time I felt less broken. Less fragile. Less willing to give up. A flow of words of comfort. I was reminded that not everyone views people as disposable. I was reminded why we put such care into who we invite in and why they are special to me.

Then a call from a friend. Then another. Then a text. Then another. People I loved. People I would only know because of NSFW. A sat down. Began reading. They reminded me why I did this to begin with. Reminded me of who I was. Who I am. I only felt alone. I wasn't.

I stared at the dark ocean. As my phone dinged with comment notifications I thought of the peace of swimming til I couldn't any more. I wiped tears off my face. I stood up. I walked til the waves were crashing on my feet.
That feeling sank me. It brought me to the lowest point of my life. I didn't want my life anymore.

Many things that hurt in that moment. The tears came easy. I remember the feeling of being all alone again. That feeling I had before NSFW. That feeling before I came out, when the shame of my existence was still tied to the cult learnings I had as a child. Where I hated myself.
I broke down. Mentally. I cracked. I lost myself in endless comments and messages. I forgot myself. Who I set myself to be. I lost touch with the core of my being.
I cried. In many ways the person I was before died. I lost him. He was more welcoming. More willing to take on peoples emotions. More willing to care. That feeling left me that day.

I remember sitting on the beach. Stressed about how I was gonna pay my rent. Concerned about people believing I was a white supremest. Saddened that a person I thought I'd spend my life with would attempt to hurt me so badly.

Within seconds people piled. A former employee. A partner of my ex-fiance. A surge of angry folks believing things that weren't true. Things that stand against so much of what we're about. What I'm about. Who I am. The pain was more than emotional. It was physical. Deep. Dark.

When I landed an influencer posted a story which claimed some pretty awful things. Calling out NSFW for being a white exclusive club. Calling me white. Sharing lies to thousands who just believed it without question.

All we can do is be better today than we were yesterday and hope tomorrow we're even better than today. I don't know, just venting on this one cause I know NSFW benefits so many I really feel more people need a place where they can feel accepted.

But I'll be strong. Continue on. Keep fighting for what I believe all should have access to. Continue finding strength in the membership and those who support us. Continue to do right by them and focus my love and attention. It's all I can do right now.

And I know it will only get worse. The target will only get larger. The claims more extreme. The anger of those who refuse to take accountability more directed. The shunned taking out their anger out on me rather than dealing with why they were removed in the first place.

I stop trusting people close to me. I distance myself further. I take months to heal. I'm still healing. I just started this thing to help people remove shame from their sex lives. A place where people could feel safe and free from judgement.

They claim I'm an egotistical narcissist cult leader who only cares about money. I cry myself to sleep for months reliving my own experiences escaping a cult and poverty. Some nights I think about how peaceful a bullet to the head would be. I get meds. I start talking to someone.
They claim we only cater to white people, we laugh at the Clubhouse cause we've always been BIPOC owned, operated, staffed and welcoming. They continue to claim I'm a white supremacist.

They claim we don't pay people, so we speed up processing and offer day of payments to performers. We double our rate and increase minimum staff payments to $20 an hour. They continue to claim we don't pay people.

They claim we protect abusers, we give evidence that the person was removed. We add four new safety measures and begin working with domestic abuse groups to assist with early detection. They continue to claim NSFW protected their ex and stop mentioning who abused them.
But regardless of this negativity, we grow. We evolve. We continue to attract new people. New members everyday. New cities opening with 24 events in September alone.

I wish it was different. I hate that we have to block these former members or warn others about them. That we have to let people know that there are people out there who may dox them, report them, and encourage people to attack them for being associated with us.

I definitely had the wrong approach in the past and would find myself on these idiotic social media fights, trying to defend myself cause a former employee is claiming they were "abused" after getting fired for making threats against people.

It's not to say we have a perfect system or that I'm not without blame. Far from that. I'm constantly evolving and trying to be a better person. We as a community are figuring out ways to manage those who refuse to accept accountability for their actions.

It's a struggle that many rumors come from people removed from our community for bad behavior. They make themselves appear as the victim to hide their own violations. They don't see their actions as abusive, so they spread rumors about me or NSFW to slow our work.

NSFW becomes the one to blame. And I quickly become the target. As someone who comes of as cis, het, male and white to anyone who doesn't know me personally, rumors are insanely effective and something I've had to deal with since our first play party.

NSFW becomes the one to blame in their minds. They stop focussing on their shitty ex or the friends they attacked on social media or issues with their own self worth and just attack the community as publicly as possible.
When approached about their misbehavior, they become defensive and quickly portray themselves as the victim, never apologizing of taking accountability for their actions.
They use words like abuser to describe me, when it's their own abuses against myself or our community that causes me to remove them in the first place.

Overall, it's a struggle when we have to remove these people from our membership cause the retaliation is usually very public, very one-sided, and tends to replace "I was told no" with "I was abused".

Also can't forget about the person who claimed I was a white supremacist to 100k fans causing death threats and so much unnecessary hate. They felt rejected at the party and thought lying about their experience was the best way to deal with it.
Another claimed we protect abusers after we provided evidence that their claim against their ex was exaggerated. We removed both the instructor and their ex from the membership.
One doxxed and threatened a member on social media, stating their position as an instructor at NSFW meant they could behave anyway they wanted.

Over the past year, we've removed a few instructors from our roster for violating our Code of Conduct. One made threats against us when we didn't cancel our event to promote theirs, vowing to destroy us by any means possible.

It's unfortunate and it really weighs on me sometimes. Not only because the person removed could be a partner, a friend, or someone many would vouch for, but also because of how some of these former members retaliate against NSFW when they are removed.
Someone who violates consent. Removal. Someone who becomes violent or makes for an unsafe environment. Removal. Someone who makes threats against our community. Removal.
The reasons are obvious. We allow someone in who violates our Code of Conduct. Someone who doesn't care about member privacy and unapologetically shares about people on social media. Removal.
I truly hate shunning. It was a major part of the cult I was raised in. I never wanted to create something where we have to shun people and yet in many ways I have.

To prevent abusers and creepers from damaging our community we enforce multiple consent policies and encourage our membership to police bad activity by submitting Creeper Reports.
It attracts people in abusive relationships. It attracts people with bad intentions. It attracts those who seek to harm others.
Running a space were sex can happen attracts all types of people including those with mental conditions, past traumas, addictions, PTSD and unexpected emotional releases.
The process definitely isn't perfect for everyone and we accept that. It's not meant to be and probably never will be.
It's us showing all the work we do to keep out creepers and abusive people.
Releasing our Creeper Reports allows us to show everyone outside of our community exactly how we manage to keep our thousands of members safe within our walls.
We want all those we welcome to our homes and Clubhouses to feel safe and to know we are always doing more to ensure that.
Cultivating consent culture is something we've always dedicated ourselves to. It's something that we will always continue to build on, never believing the job is done.
We are choosing to make this piece of our puzzle public to help reduce any belief that we protect anyone who is a danger to the safety of our community.

We are fortunate to have a team of employees and members dedicated to the safety of our community. It's because of them that we are able to grow our community and continue to offer more spaces for safe, judgement-free exploration.

Fuck, I hope this gets easier with time. Doubtful. Anyways, any suggestions for how to manage "abusers" when all evidence proves someone is lying to get back at an ex?
Blurb.
But yeah, thinking about my earliest memory again cause another person who doesn't know anything about me or our community is pushing a lie.
Is my life just going to be a constant stream of abusive people and their accusations?
I wish it was an easy thing to manage, but it's not. It doesn't happen often, but I can only imagine how much harder this will be in the future as we have more expectations to manage.

When it comes to breakups we try to stay out, but never can. Before we can even answer some people they jump online and claim their abusers are being protected. We ask for evidence. They don't provide. They lie. We can't challenge. They abuse people. We get called abusers.

I truly hate it. Scorned persons. People who feel dumped or unloved. People who have been cheated on or ditched for new love. It's crazy. I know how I am in breakups. You're unbalanced at that point. Upset. Depressed. In pain.
And for the most part our system works, except when dealing with couples. That's when shit gets difficult because we have one person demanding us to make a decision about their ex.
We have a council of members who manage reports of abuse. We take accusations very seriously.
We encourage members to come forward and promote this at all our events. We can only act if we know something happens. We strongly encourage self policing in the community to keep everyone safe.

We remove abusers quickly.  In my community we practice restorative justice. Not everyone agrees with this and they can join other communities if they don't believe that people can change. If offenses are minor there is a process for coming back.

So yeah, it hurts when someone says I'd ever protect an abuser. We don't. I don't. I don't give a fuck if someone has money or if they're a friend or a person I like, we fucking do what we have to do. One person removed to protect a community is just smart business.

I'm constantly told stories of abuse. I'm a trusted ear to many. I always listen even when the stories bring up my own pains from my past. I think everyone thinks I'm some Hefner-type, but honestly a lot of my work is just letting people vent and unload their sexual traumas.

I'm asked to weigh in on relationships. Breakups. Things I'm not involved in. Asked to make judgements against people. To remove people. Asked to side with people even when all evidence suggests they are lying.
Some people believe all forms of abuse deserve the same level response. Some ignore their own abuses against others while saying they are victims. Some who claim abuse cause love isn't returned.

I don't confess my job is easy. I'm responsible for a community. I'm considered a leader. My entire existence is dedicated to this. While it has many blessings it comes with having to confront many abusers.
This memory speeds through my head in repeat every time someone perpetuates the lie that I protect abusers.  Some left over PTSD from my adolescence.
Yes in tears. I was 8.

The earliest memory I have of my childhood was jumping on my father and biting him. He was choking my mom. I thought he'd kill her. He took his grip off. We ran to the bathroom. A knife sliding under the door as my mother asked me if I could see a life without a dad.
The reason this one hurts a bit more than some of the other things I've heard about myself or my community is because I grew uo in a home where abuse was the norm.
There are many rumors out there about NSFW and myself, but there's one particular one which always hurts. Daniel Saynt protects abusers.
